<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>From Dictionary.com<br>
gov·ern·ment n.<br>
 <br>
The act or process of governing, especially the control and administration of public policy in a political unit. <br>
The office, function, or authority of a governing individual or body. <br>
Exercise of authority in a political unit; rule. <br>
The agency or apparatus through which a governing individual or body functions and exercises authority. <br>
A governing body or organization, as:<br>
* The ruling political party or coalition of political parties in a parliamentary system. <br>
* The cabinet in a parliamentary system. <br>
* The persons who make up a governing body. <br>
A system or policy by which a political unit is governed. <br>
Administration or management of an organization, business, or institution.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Is it really just me ...but you are looking at a horse and calling it a donkey.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A rotation is an agreement between the parties that can kill a mobile in Everquest.  It regulates the ethics and morals that the involved parties stick to when dealing with each other over the spawn in question. It is not a law, it's not an absolute.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not exactly true, is it?  &quot;Regulation&quot; is a synonym for &quot;rule, law, policy&quot; ...look them all up.  If this 'agreement' was kept between 'the parties that can kill a mobile in Everquest', you could almost have a valid argument ...but it isn't.  Once this 'agreement' is made and agreed on by 'the parties that can kill a mobile in Everquest', it is passed as regulation (law) to everyone on the Rathe server to be abided by regardless of whether they can kill that mobile or not.  As long as a guild is not currently fighting that mobile, the law governing that mob is absolute (we have no say).  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Note that I use the words 'the involved parties' here. I do this because until you are killing said mobile the rotation agreement doesn't concern you and doesn't effect you or your gameplay one jot.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I am bound by the laws of that agreement even though I personally cannot kill any of the mobs by myself.  My guild is bound by the laws of the rotations, even though we may not BE ON THAT ROTATION.<br>
